fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Proof by contradiction. Assume for contradiction f(x) were reducible, say f(x)=a(x)b(x) in R[x] where a(x) and b(x) are nonconstant polynomials. Reducing this equation modulo P and using the assumption on the coefficients of f(x), we obtain the equation
x^{n}=\overline {a(x)b(x)}
in (R/P)[x] where the bar denotes the polynomials with coefficients reduced modulo P.

Now, we look at:
\begin {align} d(x_{k+1},x_{k}) & \leq  d(f(x_{k}),f(x_{k-1}))\\ &\leq  cd(x_{k},x_{k-1})\\ &\leq  c^{k}d(x_{1},x_{0})\hbox { by induction}\\ &\leq  c^{k}d(f(x_{0}),x_{0})\end {align}
For any non-negative integers m,n\in \mathbb {N}_{0} with m>n we have (using the triangle inequality),
\begin {align} d(x_{m},x_{n}) & \leq  d(x_{n},x_{n+1}) + d(x_{n+1},x_{n+2}) + … + d(x_{m-1},x_{m})\\ &\leq  (c^{n}+c^{n+1}+…+c^{m-1})d(f(x_{0}),x_{0})\\ &\leq  c^{n}\left (\frac {1-c^{m-n}}{1-c}\right )d(f(x_{0}),x_{0})\\ &\leq \frac {c^{n}}{1-c}d(f(x_{0}),x_{0}) \end {align}
since 0\leq  c<1, the numerator is bounded by 1-c^{m-n}\leq  1 which is how we get the last line. Now, taking n\to \infty  we see c^{n}\to 0 so d(x_{n},x_{m})\to 0. This proves the sequence (x_{n}) is Cauchy. But by hypothesis, (X,d) is complete, so (x_{n}) converges in X. Let us call its limit x_{*}, so x\to  x_{*} in X.

We repeat this process inductively and obtain a Continuous function between metric spaces of nonempty closed subsets (A_{n}). We see \mathop {\textrm {diam}}\nolimits (A_{n})\leq  2^{-n} and A_{n+1}\subseteq  A_{n}. Since X is complete, we can use Cantor intersection theorem. (Each A_{n} cannot be covered by finitely many U_{\alpha }.) There exists a point x_{0}\in  X which is the unique intersection point
\{x_{0}\} = \bigcap ^{\infty }_{n=1}A_{n}
There exists a particular U_{\alpha _{0}} in our open cover containing x_{0}\in  U_{\alpha _{0}}. (There may be several, we only need the fact there exists at least one.) Since U_{\alpha _{0}} is open, there exists an r_{0}>0 such that B_{r_{0}}(x_{0})\subseteq  U_{\alpha _{0}}. We know \mathop {\textrm {diam}}\nolimits (A_{n})\to 0 so there exists some index N\in \mathbb {N} such that for all n\geq  N we have
A_{n}\subseteq  B_{r_{0}}(x_{0})\subseteq  U_{\alpha _{0}}
This is a contradiction, because we specifically chose these A_{n} to be impossible to cover with finitely many U_{\alpha } (and we just covered them with a single one). Hence the contradiction. Hence X is compact.

(2)\implies (3) Assume X is compact. Let (x_{n}) be a sequence in X. We want to show (x_{n}) has a convergent Subsequence in X. Define the set
E = \{x_{n}\in  X\mid  n\in \mathbb {N}\}
to be the set of terms appearing in the sequence. Then either E is a finite set or not.
